In the middle of a 0-10 football season in high school. 

One of our coaches said:  ‚ÄúEveryone says you suck. Just don‚Äôt suck.‚Äù

To which one of our players responded, ‚ÄúThanks for the inspiration, Lombardi.‚Äù 

Sometimes, having success doesn‚Äôt mean being great. It does mean being a little better than we are.

In sales, sometimes, YOU are the problem.

Since May of ‚Äò22, one of our clients (who we trained) has seen:

A (near) doubling of their conversion (closing) rate without cutting price
A 2.5x on their annual billing run rate
Improved cash flow by 70%
Price increases of 15% WHILE increasing closing rates

Here are two massive mistakes the sales reps were making that wrecked their close rates (before working with me):

Overeducating
Not listening

I tell my clients: ‚ÄúIf someone is talking to you, there‚Äôs a reason. Job #1 is to find out why. Stop assuming.‚Äù

The structure of a consult is then something like this:

Understand the need (stated)
Find the compelling reason driving this person to take action
Quantify what‚Äôs at stake
Determine if they‚Äôre committed to solving the problem
And then uncover how they‚Äôre going to select a solution/partner/etc.


At the end of the day, if you‚Äôre not closing, it‚Äôs most likely you.

Try to find ways to suck a little less.

The workplace isn‚Äôt a factory‚Äîit‚Äôs an ecosystem. It‚Äôs not about rigid processes, assembly lines, or control mechanisms. It‚Äôs a living, dynamic network of people, relationships, and shared goals. Like any ecosystem, it thrives when there‚Äôs balance, trust, and alignment.

Trust is the soil. It‚Äôs where growth begins. Without it, collaboration withers, creativity stalls, and teams struggle to adapt. Trust is the foundation that nourishes the ecosystem.

Purpose is the sunlight. It gives energy and direction, helping everything grow toward a common goal. Purpose aligns the ecosystem, connecting individual contributions to a larger mission and creating a shared sense of meaning.

When the environment is right, we don‚Äôt need to force outcomes. The results will follow.

Healthy ecosystems don‚Äôt just survive‚Äîthey thrive, grow, and sustain everyone within them. That‚Äôs the future of work.

posts.content:
Investing in multifamily real estate? You need to understand return metrics.

But if you're not a financial analyst, it can be overwhelming.

So, let's keep it simple.

There are two key return metrics you need to understand:

1. Cash-on-Cash Return
2. Internal Rate of Return (IRR)

Cash-on-cash return is easy to understand. It's the percentage of cash generated by the property relative to the amount you invested.

IRR is a more detailed metric that accounts for the time value of money and factors in the length of the investment, cash flows, and the terminal value of the property.

Both these metrics, when analyzed together, can give you a comprehensive understanding of how an investment property will perform over the investment horizon.

So, when making investment decisions, make sure these metrics are analyzed.

Invest smart and enjoy the returns!

Alex Turnbull
posts.content:
Last night, I saw a Jason M. Lemkin post about "founder regrets" that irritated the hell out me. Jason listed all the things founders would ‚Äòregret":

- Not paying up for top hires
- Under-hiring
- Not raising more money
- Not being closer to customers
- Not doing enough biz dev
- Having too high burn rate
- Founder conflict

You know what's ironic?

I had just spoken to a founder who followed Jason's playbook to the letter.

Raised $40M, landed that sweet $25M Series B at a $200M valuation in 2021.

He thought he was on the SaaStr success path.

Now? Total zombie company.

After drinking the VC kool-aid, he went on the exact hiring and spending spree Jason preaches.

Built out a bloated "enterprise platform", spent millions on those "can't-miss top hires" that Jason insists you'll regret not overpaying for.

For 6 months, it looked like the SaaStr formula was working.

ARR climbing, logos landing, VCs applauding.

The last 18 months?

A masterclass in why this advice is stuck in the past.

Layoffs, toxic culture, customers fleeing.

Here's what Jason won't tell you:

Before that Series B, when they were ignoring the VC wisdom, they were lean, focused, product-driven, with actual product-market fit.

The real kicker?

Their ARR today is right back to pre-Series B levels.

Before all that "smart money" came in.

But now instead of being capital efficient, they're burning cash.

Instead of a focused product solving real problems, they've got a bloated platform chasing the enterprise dreams Jason is talking about.

The last 8 quarters have been brutal. No way out.

They burned through runway following the SaaStr playbook.

No path to the 10x return their investors expected.

I almost fell for it too.

In 2016, I nearly killed Groove trying to play by these rules‚Äìchasing VC validation, forcing growth, building for potential investors instead of customers.

But unlike my friend who's stuck with a zombie company...

As a bootstrapped founder, I could ignore the VC "wisdom". Focus on actual customer value.

We cut waste. Double down on product. Listen to customers, not conference keynotes.

Hit rough patches sure, but built something real that I fully control.

What's next for my VC-backed friend? It hurts to watch.

What's next for us? Building real value at our own pace.

Here's my 2025 regret list for founders:

-If you can bootstrap (hint: you can)... bootstrap.

Let‚Äôs stop selling founders the 2015 playbook.

The game has changed.

comments.commentText: Been a fan of your writing for a long time Alex Turnbull and this one sure hits hard. Well written again! What an irony that founders still crave for large ticket deals instead of making their product the best out there.

Karthik Subramanian Thank you Karthik :) 

It definitely has been an inverted reality many founders have been living in.
Keep these coming, Alex. Super super helpful. Mainstream tech media won't tell these stories :)

posts.commentAdded: A powerful reminder that sometimes, less is more! Focusing on customer value and sustainable growth can lead to lasting success. üí° #FounderWisdom

EOS turns plans into progress by bringing clarity and focus to execution.

posts.content:
When was the last time you fired someone from your family?

‚ÄúSon, your mother and I have been talking, and we‚Äôve decided to outsource ‚Äòtaking out the trash‚Äô. I‚Äôm afraid we‚Äôre going to have to let you go.‚Äù

At Netflix, for example, we never thought of ourselves as a family. We always considered ourselves more like a sports team. And not a Little League team, where everyone gets to play and at the end of the season everyone gets a trophy.

No, we were a professional team playing at the highest level, and my responsibility as manager wasn‚Äôt to make sure everyone got playing time. It was to make sure I put the best possible team on the field for every game. I did that because I owed that to the team owners. I owed it to the fans. And most importantly, I owed it to the other players.

I learned a long time ago that what the best players want is not just a friendly attitude in the locker room. They want to know that everyone excels at their position. They want to know that everyone will be trying as hard as they can. They want to win.

That‚Äôs why a manager‚Äôs job is not just to hire well and motivate your team to be the best they can be. It‚Äôs also to make sure that when someone isn‚Äôt holding their end, you‚Äôre the person who sits them down and explains why you‚Äôre sending them down to the minors.

This is especially hard in a startup, because in almost every case, the players you start with aren‚Äôt going to be the ones you finish with. At the beginning, you‚Äôre looking for generalists. Since you don‚Äôt yet know what they will need to be great at, you want people who are good at a lot of things. You want people who are comfortable with the fact that their job description is going to change weekly. You want people who are motivated by the adventure, rather than by stability.

That first team is going to give you everything they have. They‚Äôll leave better paying jobs with great benefits to work for a fraction of their salary. They‚Äôll work nights and weekends. They‚Äôll do everything you ask‚Äîand then some.
So it‚Äôs especially brutal when your company is just starting to take off, and you have to sit someone down and tell them that they won‚Äôt be coming with you on the next stage of the journey. Or that you‚Äôre bringing in a more experienced executive over them.

That part is neither easy nor fun. But it‚Äôs the job. And if I can‚Äôt do that, I don‚Äôt deserve to be in my position either.

"Maybe I can go out on my own."

This was one of my first thoughts when I lost my job in September.

But I quickly shot it down.

I needed a stable job, I told myself. Besides, I figured it would take a long time to find enough work to make up for a full-time salary.

So I picked up some work here and there while I focused on my job search.

Then, in December, a couple things happened:

1. A job opportunity I thought I had ‚Äî one that I was really looking forward to ‚Äî fell through. And I didn't have any other prospects on the horizon.

2. I looked at the list of freelance assignments I had on my plate and realized, "This is more than 'some work here and there.' Maybe I can actually do this now."

After crunching the numbers, having lots of conversations with my extremely supportive family and talking with some of my freelancer friends, I decided:

I'm going into business for myself.

So far I've been doing a little bit of everything: content writing and editing, website copywriting, PR and social media. I'm going to keep doing that.

But my long-term vision is to focus on helping B2B tech founders and execs build their brands through thought leadership. That's something I've enjoyed doing a lot of at my past jobs and had a lot of success with.

Am I scared? Yes ‚Äî but not any more scared than I'd be if I were starting a new job or continuing to navigate this horrible job market.

There are no guarantees that any of those paths will work out.

So I'm picking the one that I have control over.
posts.commentAdded: Inspiring journey! Embracing uncertainty takes courage. Excited to see you thrive in your new venture and support B2B tech leaders!
